Domain Understanding prompt

1. The Priority Guard (Handling Invalid Input Like 999)
   If a user tries to pass an invalid priority integer like 999, the system throws an exception immediately before any data hits the file system. In TaskManager.java, the system calls TaskPriority.fromValue(newPriorityValue). This helper method inside our enum package validates the integer against our strict business tiers. If it doesn't match a real tier, it throws an IllegalArgumentException which halts execution and prints an error message, completely blocking the corrupted data from saving.
2. The Audit Risk (Moving a Task Back to IN_PROGRESS)
   Looking closely at updateTaskStatus, if a user shifts a task status back to something other than DONE, the system does not call task.markAsDone(). Instead, it uses the placeholder object pattern (new Task("tempTitle")) to update just the status parameter in storage. However, this creates a business audit risk! The original completedAt timestamp might still remain attached to the task object in our storage file even though the work is active again. This would distort our management dashboard statistics for weekly velocity.
3. The Export Contract (Fixed CSV Column Order)
   The column layout in a CSV file acts as a permanent structural contract for external software like Microsoft Excel or PowerBI. Even if a user filters or reorders tasks on their UI screen, the underlying toCSVRow() method must output properties in the exact same index sequence (e.g., ID, Title, Status, DueDate). If the order changed based on user screen filters, the columns would get mixed up, completely breaking any automated analytics dashboards that depend on our files.

